               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18180909-320-person2212">
                  JOHN 
                  EVERLEIGH
               <interp inst="t18180909-320-person2212" type="surname" value="EVERLEIGH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-320-person2212" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18180909-320-person2212" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . On the 24th of July, about eight o'clock in the evening, I was going through the posts on<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="181809090100"></xptr>
                  <placeName id="t18180909-320-crimeloc1761">Saffron-hill</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-320-crimeloc1761" type="placeName" value="Saffron-hill"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18180909-320-crimeloc1761" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18180909-320-off1759 t18180909-320-crimeloc1761"></join>, and saw some men standing there; they divided; as I came to the posts the prisoner rushed against me with great violence, and put his hands to my fob. I felt him draw my watch out, and immediately secured him; the others closed upon me. I took the watch from him. The gang demanded of me to let him go. I refused and held him fast. I had another person with me, or they would have rescued him. They wanted me to take him into a house to search him. I held him about ten minutes, when Limbrick and Read came and took him. I never let him go.</p>
               <p>JOHN LIMBRICK. I am an officer. Read and I were going by, and took the prisoner in charge from the prosecutor.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The prosecutor was in liquor, and said I took his watch. I know nothing about it.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18180909-320-verdict1762" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18180909-320-verdict1762" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs> Aged 18.</p>
